{
  "answer": "**In *San Hyan Kamahayanikan* (a single-chapter work), the doctrine of the Five Tathāgatas (Pañcatathāgata)—Vairocana, Akṣobhya, Ratnasambhava, Amitābha, and Amoghasiddhi—is first referenced during the exposition of the Perfection of Morality (*śīlapāramitā*), as part of rules for bodily conduct after consecration.**[^1]\n\nThis initial mention presupposes the Five Tathāgatas as abiding in the practitioner's head (lest they depart if touched improperly), prior to any naming. The five are then first explicitly named and linked to breath practices shortly before the text's advanced yogic instructions.[^2] The doctrine is systematically articulated soon after, identifying them as emerging from Śākyamuni (with Lokeśvara and Vajrapāṇi), their seed-syllables, wisdoms, consorts, associations with aggregates/elements/poisons, etc., comprising much of the text's second half.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-638b90).\n[^2]: *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-cf2520).\n[^3]: *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-f72091).",
